{{- /*
config-secrets-key.tmpl — READ (never create) the machine-local AES key that
encrypts the secrets prompted by .chezmoi.toml.tmpl (luksPassphraseCipher /
mokPasswordCipher) so they are stored in ~/.config/chezmoi/chezmoi.toml as
ciphertext, never plaintext. The key lives ONLY in the user keyring (Secret
Service) under service=chezmoi-config-secrets / user=<username>. This partial is
the one the DECRYPT consumers use (run_onchange_after_luks-tpm2,
run_onchange_before_ubuntu): it must stay read-only, because a host that stored
a cipher but lost its keyring entry would otherwise get a fresh random key that
cannot decrypt the old ciphertext. The GET-OR-CREATE sibling
.chezmoitemplates/config-secrets-key-ensure.tmpl is what seeds the key, and only
where a secret is being stored — the config template's prompt path — since
chezmoi renders (and prompts on) the config template BEFORE the
.install-prerequisites.{sh,ps1} read-source-state hook that also seeds it runs.

LINUX-ONLY, matching the hook's key generation: both consumers are
Linux-gated, and macOS's keyring backend (go-keyring drives
/usr/bin/security) can escalate to a BLOCKING SecurityAgent dialog on a
locked keychain, hanging a headless render forever. On any other OS this
partial renders the empty string, i.e. the secret-absent skip path.

Read FAIL-SOFT via `timeout 10 chezmoi secret keyring get` in a subshell:
chezmoi's built-in `keyring` template function hard-errors when no keyring
daemon is reachable (headless, TTY, container, CI — it even tries to exec
dbus-launch), which would break every render there, and the timeout turns a
Secret Service prompter that never answers into a skip instead of a stuck
render. This wrapper yields an empty string on any failure, and callers
treat an empty key as "secret unavailable" and take their skip path.
`.chezmoi.executable` (not a bare `chezmoi`) keeps this working when the
running binary is not on PATH.

Rotation/loss: a lost or rotated keyring entry cannot decrypt previously
stored ciphertexts — decryptAES then yields garbage (or a render error). To
recover, re-prompt with `chezmoi init --data=false` (or delete the *Cipher
keys from ~/.config/chezmoi/chezmoi.toml and re-run `chezmoi init`).
*/ -}}
{{- if eq .chezmoi.os "linux" -}}
{{-   output "sh" "-c" (printf "timeout 10 %q secret keyring get --service=chezmoi-config-secrets --user=%q 2>/dev/null || true" .chezmoi.executable .chezmoi.username) | trim -}}
{{- end -}}
